{"key":"post-6539804","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>6539804</id>\n<content>Simply do what the commercial farms do and cut the base off with a knife.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Small fruit size is related to substrate moisture content.&amp;nbsp; It's easy to hydrate a substrate block during fruiting by simply pouring water around the edges so it slides down and under the substrate.&amp;nbsp; If you pour a few tablespoons of water around the edges a couple of times a day, the substrate will readily absorb it and transfer the moisture to your fruits.&amp;nbsp;  Cubes will benefit from a casing layer, but by no means is one necessary to get a nice flush of large fruits.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Yes, wax paper helps, but if humidity is already 99%, it's not necessary.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>6539817</next>\n<prev>6539774</prev>\n<first>6538045</first>\n<last>6543872</last>\n<when>1170868403</when>\n<utime>02/07/07 07:13 PM</utime>\n</post>"}